1. General

In spring 1996, when I released a little program called "TextConv" at
the AmiNet, I did not expect to receive such a huge amount of
reactions or to become published in an Amiga magazine (Germans "Amiga
Spezial 2/96").
Because of these reactions I decided to continue the development of
TextConv up to this new version.

Please excuse the long time that I need for finishing this version.
The causes are that I had to force my studies at the university
because I didn`t get any more money form the austrian gouvernment
and the very long beta test time between the versions 1.50 and 1.51
because I tried to deliver a nearly bug-free program.

At this point, thanks to all the users of TextConv whose bug reports
and suggestions helped me developing TextConv.

Please excuse the translation mistakes, notice that english is a
foreign language for me.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@NEXT "System"
@PREV "General"
@TOC "MAIN"
2. Introduction

Why an ASCII-text-converter?

Did you ever try to edit a MS-DOS-text with a MS-Windows-editor?
Or a Windows-text with OS/2?
Or a Macintosh-text with an Amiga?

If you can answer one or more of these questions with YES,
you already got the answer;-)


Well, the real cause is the following:

The ASCII-charset (ASCII=Amercian Standard Code For Information
Interchange) isn`t defined very exactly. Only the first 127 chars
are equal for all computer systems, the rest varies from computer
system to computer system (in this range are the most special chars and
umlauts placed).
Also the code for a line feed is different at the several system
platforms:


Charsets:

 ANSI ASCII:   Amiga, UNIX, Windows
 PC-850 ASCII: MS-DOS, OS/2 *
 MAC ASCII:    Apple Macintosh **
 ATARI ASCII:  Atari ***

 *   The PC-850 charset is also known as IBM-charset
 **  The Macintosh-charset is similar to the ANSI-ASCII charset
 *** The Atari-charset is similar to the PC-850 charset


Linefeed code:

 Amiga,UNIX:              LF 
 DOS,OS/2,Windows, Atari: CR+LF 
 Mac:                     CR


When you want to transfer text files between these systems you have to
bring the files into the right shape, and for this a converter like
TextConv is needed.

It`s important to know that this conversion usually causes losses;
that means, as example, if a MS-DOS-text becomes converted to the
Amiga format and than back to the MS-DOS-format, the new and the old
file are not identically. The reason for this is that the Amiga
does not have some specific PC-characters (graphics chars,for example).
During conversion, this chars are converted to similar Amiga-chars,
so that the original char is lost. The same priciple is valid for
Macintosh- or Atari-texts.
If, for example, an Atari-Text should be converted to the
Macintosh-format, it isn`t useful to convert the text first into the
Amiga-format (to read it with the Amiga or something else) and
then convert it from the Amiga- to the Atari-format, because
there are losses on the way from Atari to Amiga AND from Amiga to
Macintosh.
The conversion should always take the original file as source.
 


@ENDNODE

@NODE "System" "System requirements, compatibility"
@NEXT "Warranty"
@PREV "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"
3. System requirements, compatibility

- 1 Amiga (or more :-) or the Amiga-emulator UAE
- Kickstart/Workbench 2.04 or higher
- Helvetica 11 - font in the FONTS:-directory
- about 230 kB free memory
- a minimum workbench screen hight of 256 pixels

There shouldn`t be any problemes if these requirements are fulfilled
(please read the notices at the end of this section!).
TextConv V1.51 has been tested with the following configurations:

1) SCT Amiga2000C mode 1:
   Base Amiga 2000C, Kickstart/Workbench 2.04, 2.1, 3.1
   2MB chip RAM, ECS Graphics via Multivision2000 flickerfixer
   Blizzard 2060/50, 28MB RAM, Blizzard SCSI-controller
   PicassoII gfxboard (original Picasso WB-emulation and Shareware-
   CybergraphX-emulation)

2) SCT Amiga2000C mode 2:
   Base Amiga 2000C, Kickstart/Workbench 2.04, 2.1, 3.1
   2MB chip RAM, ECS Graphics via Multivision2000 flickerfixer
   Original MC68000, 7.14MHz, BSC Tandem IDE HD
   FastRAM-configurations:
   - 0MB FastRAM
   - 2MB FastRAM from PicassoII with APM (Add Picasso Mem)
   - 4MB FastRAM from GoldenGate486SLC/2 Bridgeboard with "moremem"

3) SCT UAE 0.68c for MS-DOS
   Intel Pentium PC, 75/100/166MHz, 48MB RAM
   MS-DOS 7.0, Windows 95, OS/2 Warp4
   Kickstart/Workbench version 3.1
   UAE-configuration: 68000 and 68020-version,
   system requirements from above must be fulfilled.

4) SCT UAE 0.68 Rel.14 for Windows
   Intel Pentium PC, 166MHz, 48MB RAM
   Windows95, DirectX 3.0
   Kickstart/Workbench version 3.1
   UAE-configuration: 68020-version,
   system requirements from above must be fulfilled.

5) MDS UAE 0.68c for MS-DOS
   Intel Pentium PC, 150MHz, 32MB RAM
   MS-DOS 7.0, Windows 95
   Kickstart/Workbench version 3.1
   UAE-configuration: 68000 und 68020-version,
   system requirements from above must be fulfilled.

Notice 1:
The GUI is designed for WB-resolutions with a 4:3-proportion
(e.g. Hires-Interlace, Productivity, (S)VGA-resolutions from
GFX-boards). Such a mode isn`t necessary, but it looks much better;-)

Notice 2:
In case of an access to a CrossDos-drive the CrossDos-commodity
(Note: the commodity, not the driver) MAY NOT BE ACTIVE,
because this commodity also makes a (partial) conversion of textfiles
like the way TextConv does. This leads to results that are not
desired. Files that have been converted with the CrossDos-commodity
usually can`t become further processed via TextConv, because the
conversion that CrossDos does is too inaccurate.

Notice 3:
If text should be transfered to the Mac-emulator ShapeShifter via
Clipboard, the format of these texts has to be Amiga-ACSII-format,
because ShapeShifter converts text to the Mac-format itself when
they are imported from the Amiga-clipboard.



@ENDNODE

