5. Installation

The installation is very easy, so I thought that it isn`t
necessary to write an Installerscript:

Just copy the TextConv-folder into the desired target directory
(at the Workbench via drag the folder, with CLI/Shell via the command
copy or with a DOS-tool like DOpus).
No specific system setups (e.g. ASSIGN`s) are necessary.
But you have to be sure that the system requirements are fulfilled.
ATTENTION: the folder "ConvTabs" has to be placed into the same
directory as the main program "TextConv"!


5.1 Additional installation notes

If you want to use TextConv via programs like "@{"ToolManager" LINK "Credits"}" or
"@{"Directory Opus" LINK "Credits"}" please read the notes at the section
"@{"Starting TextConv" LINK "Starting"}" and the manuals of the respective program.
Some dockbrushes e.g. for Toolmanager are included in this
archive (directory "Docks").


Toolmanager-settings:

ExecType:  CLI
Stack:     4096
Priority:  0
Delay:     0
Arguments: activated

Be careful with the correct path names!!
The setting "Current Directory" has to be set to the program folder,
otherwise the conversion tables in the folder "ConvTabs" will not
be found!!


DirectoryOpus-settings:

Type:         AmigaDOS
Command line: [PFAD] TextConv {F}
              ({F}...all selected files will be handed over)
Flags:        Run asynchronously
              Workbench to front
              (TextConv-window will always be opened at the WB-Screen)



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Starting" "Starting of TextConv"
@NEXT "Using"
@PREV "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"
6. Starting of TextConv

The usual starting of TextConv happens via Workbench or CLI:

- Workbench: with double-click on the TextConv-icon
- CLI/Shell: textconv [[PATH] filename [PATH] filename ..]
  There can be loaded max. 100 files at once.

Because of the CLI-interface the starting of TextConv via programs
like @{"Toolmanager" LINK "Credits"} or @{"DirectoryOpus" LINK "Credits"} is recommended (see section
"@{"Installation" LINK "Installation"}").
When using Toolmanger, the desired files are just dragged to the
respective dock; in DirectoryOpus, the desired files are marked
first, then TextConv can be started by pressing the TextConv-button.
Please notice that max. 100 files can be handed over!!



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Using" "Using TextConv"
@NEXT "Gadgets"
@PREV "Starting"
@TOC "MAIN"
7.  Using TextConv

After the start the TextConv-window will be opend.
It`s splitted into three groups:

-control buttons (group program)
-setting buttons (group settings)
-status line

If no files has been handed over at the start, the status line says
"No files loaded", otherwise "# files selected - START to convert".

IMPORTANT: Files that have been overhanded at startup or that have
been "loaded" at the ASL-request won`t be really loaded, they just
become marked for loading. The files will be loaded into memory
during the conversion process. That`s the cause why the settings
can be choosen after the "loading" process (but not after the
start of the conversion process).

If you didn`t overhand files at the startup, you have to press the
"Load files.."-button. An ASL-requester appears, from where you can
choose up to 100 files (multiselect by pressing the SHIFT-button;
only possible, when all files are located in the same folder).
This ASL-requester is also drag&drop-able, this means you can drag
files form a Workbench-window itno the requester.  This causes
that you change the actual directory to the one you dropped into the
requester. Please notice that only the first marked file will be
overhanded!

When using the program "@{"ArcHandler" LINK "Credits"}" its also possible to convert
files directly out of LHA-archives. At the moment only reading from
archives is possible, writing NOT!

After the choosing of the desired files you have to tell the
program the @{"format" LINK "Introduction"} of the source files and into which format they
should be converted. This happens with the following cycle-gadgets
(see also "@{"Description of the gadgets" LINK "Gadgets"}"):
 - "Read files as.." (format source file(s))
 - "Save files as.." (format target file(s))
 - "Conversion mode" (with or without contol chars respectively
    remove control chars or convert only control chars;
    usually always "Standardconversion", this means convert chars and
    control chars; see also "@{"Practical examples" LINK "Examples"}")
 - "Save mode" (how to save the files)

Press the start button to start the conversion process after you have
done your desired settings. Depeding on the kind of "Save mode" you
might be asked about the target directory or -file names.
 
If a file exists with the same name as the one that TextConv wants to
write, a requester appers and asks whether the file should become
overwritten or a new name should be set.
Notice that the file that actually becomes converted can`t be
overwritten (this means replacing of a file is not possible).
The gadgets and menus are switched off during the conversion process
to avoid unwanted inputs.

The status of the conversion process is displayed at the status line,
the name of the actual file and the conversion in percent is visible.
If everything has been alright, the message "File(s) converted" is
displayed at the status line, otherwise an error message will be
shown.

After a short period all files have been converted and now you
can convert the same files with other settings, you can load new files
or you can exit the program by pressing the "Quit" button.
After pressing the Quit-button you will be asked whether you
really want to finish or not.


@{"Description of the gadgets" LINK "Gadgets"}
@{"Practical examples" LINK "Examples"}



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Gadgets" "Description of the gadgets"
@NEXT "Examples"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"
7.1 Description of the gadgets:



Group Program:

- Load files:     Used for choosing the files to load; directory can
                  be choosen by drag&drop, multiselect by pressing the
                  SHIFT-button; at multiselect all files have to be
                  located at the same directory (this is a restriction
                  caused by the ASL-requester, when overhanding files
                  via CLI-interface this restriction doesn`t exist).
                  A maximum of 100 files (any size) can be overhanded.

- Start:          Starts the conversion process. During the conversion
                  all gadgets are switched off.

- About TextConv: Opens a window containing general informations
                  about TextConv.

- Quit:           Quits TextConv. Before quitting a requester appears
                  that asks whether finishing really or not.

All the points above are also accessable via the "Project"-menu.


Group settings:

- Read files as:         Sets the source format.
                         Possible settings are:
                         - Amiga ASCII (UNIX)
                         - MS-DOS/OS2-ASCII (IBM/CP850)
@                         - MS-Windows ANSI
                         - Macintosh
                         - Atari

- Save files as:         Sets the target format.
                         Possible settings are:
                         - Amiga ASCII (UNIX)
                         - MS-DOS/OS2-ASCII (IBM/CP850)
                         - MS-Windows ANSI
                         - Macintosh
                         - Atari

- Conversion mode:       Sets the conversion mode for the control
                         chars.
                         Possible settings are:
                         - Standardconversion
                           Control chars and normal chars will be
                           converted.
                           Use: this is the standard setting
                         - Don`t convert control chars
                           Normal chars will be converted, control

                           chars will be not changed.
                           Use: for special problems
                         - Remove control chars
                           Normal chars will be converted, control
                           chars will be removed.
                           Use: preparing the text for later use
                           with a word processor (for automatic
                           justified lines or something similar)
                           ATTENTION: indentions will also be
                           removed!
                         - Convert only control chars
                           Normal chars will not be changed, control
                           chars will be converted.
                           Use: for special problems

- Save mode:             Sets the way that converted files should be
                         saved.
                         Possible settings are:
                         - each file seperate
                           Useful for a small number of files
                           For each file the target directory and the
                           target name is asked (the original name
                           is NOT overhanded automatically!).
                         - same dir. another extension
                           In this case the source- and target
                           directory are the same; the converted files
                           are marked with a special extension that
                           depends on the target format:
                           Possible extensions are:
                           - .ami...Amiga or Unix-format
                           - .dos...MS-DOS or OS/2-format
                           - .win...MS-Windows-format
                           - .mac...Apple-Macintosh-format
                           - .ata...Atari-format
                         - into another directory
                           All files will be written into a
                           specified target dirctory; the filenames
                           won`t be changed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Examples" "Practical examples"
@NEXT "Bugs"
@PREV "Gadgets"
@TOC "MAIN"
7.2 Practical examples


1. The normal case - direct conversion between 2 formats

   Problem description: A MS-DOS ASCII-text should be converted
                        to the Amiga-format.
   Solution: The settings for this case are:
             - Read files as: IBM/MSDOS/OS2 ASCII
             - Save files as: Amiga ASCII (Unix)
             - Conversion mode: Standardconversion
             - Save mode: (any)
             The text can now be used with any Amiga text editor.

   Problem description: Some Atari-texts should be converted to
                        Mac-format; the texts should be viewed
                        at the Amiga before processed at the Mac.
   Solution: Because of the problem that the conversion causes
             losses, the way Atari->Amiga->Mac should be avoided.
             It`s better to create both the Amiga and the Macintosh
             files from the original sourcefile.
             After the file selection, we first create the Amiga
             files:
             - Read files as: Atari ST
             - Save files as: Amiga ASCII (Unix)
             - Conversion mode: Standardconversion
             - Save mode: same dir. another extension
             Press the "Start"-button to start the conversion.
             The source folder now contains also the converted files,
             marked with the extension .ami.
             Because TextConv remembers the source files also after
             the conversion, you just have to change the setting
             - Save files as: Apple Macintosh;
             you don`t have to select the source files again.
             After pressing the Start-button the Macintosh-files
             will be created (Extension .mac).
             If you use the setting "same dir. another extension",
             be careful that the max. allowed number of chars
             for filenames  (Amiga: 25 or 30) doesn`t exceed.


2. Prepare ASCII-text for word processing

   Problem description: An Amiga-ASCII-text should be handed over to
                        the Amiga word-processor FinalCopy, so that
                        flushed line justification is possible.
   Solution: To create flushed text, the lines may not be ended with
             line feed. When a word processor detects such a line
             feed, it` s interpreted as an indent.
             To avoid this, the LF-codes have to be removed.
             Because FinalCopy has no import filter that removes
             line feeds automatically, a converter like TextConv has
             to do this job.
             The settings for this problem are:
             - Read files as: Amiga ASCII (Unix)
             - Save files as: Amiga ASCII (Unix)
             - Conversion mode: Remove control chars
             - Save mode: (any)
             Notice that indents and empty lines also will be
             removed (this may be changed at the next release).

   Problem description: A Mac-ASCII-text should be handed over to
                        MS-Winword, so that flushed line justification
                        is possible.
   Solution: In contrast to FinalCopy Winword has a text import filter
             that is able to remove linefeeds (but difficulty depends
             on the respective WinWord-version).
             Because of that, that a conversion has to be done via
             TextConv from Mac to PC-ASCII anyway, the removing of
             the LF`s can be done in the same step.
             The settings are:
             - Read files as: Apple Macintosh
             - Save files as: MS Windows ANSI
             - Conversion mode: Remove control chars
             - Save mode: (any)
             The file can now be imported into WinWord via the "Text
             only" import filter.
             Attention: also indets will be removed.


3. An example for a special problem

   Problem description: An e-mail has been received on an OS/2-PC,
                        the contents of the mail is a special
                        Amiga-ASCII-text (concrete: a registration
                        file), which has to be saved from an
                        OS/2-editor (via copy&paste).
                        This transfer causes a changing of the control
                        chars form LF to CRLF.

   Solution: The normal chars are neither changed from the
             transmission via clipboard nor from the saving process
             of the editor; only the control chars will be changed
             from LF to CRLF.
             The text is still in Amiga-ASCII-code; the control chars
             are in MS-DOS-format.
             The correct setting to solve this problem are:
             - Read files as: IBM/MSDOS/OS2 ASCII
             - Save files as: Amiga ASCII (Unix)
             - Conversion mode: Convert only control chars
             - Save mode: (any)
             With the setting "Convert only control chars" only the
             changing from LF to CRLF is undone, all normal chars
             are not changed.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs" "Known Bugs"
@NEXT "Future"
@PREV "Examples"
@TOC "MAIN"
8.  Known bugs

Not one program all over world is 100% bug-free, TextConv is no
exception. Following bugs and problems are known and will be
removed (I hope so) at the next release:

8.1 Internal bugs

- In very rare cases TextConv thinks that a file already exists
  (Warning before overwriting) although this isn`t TRUE.

8.1 Problems with other programs

- When overhanding files from @{"ToolManager" LINK "Credits"} it may happen, that TextConv
  starts with the status message "No files loaded". This should not
  be caused by TextConv, but from a restriction of the maximum length
  of a CLI parameter line from ToolManager.
- When using TextConv with @{"UAE 0.68c for MS-DOS" LINK "Credits"}, there can be problems
  with direct (write) access to virtual DOS-disks; especially when UAE
  has been started from Win95.
  This should be a bug in UAE, because other programs have the same
  problem.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Future" "Future development"
@NEXT "History"
@PREV "Bugs"
@TOC "MAIN"
9.  Future development

The basic development of TextConv is finished with the release of this
version.
The following changes are planned:

- Possibility to keep indents at the setting "Remove control chars"
- Changing of the file management, so that the last choosen directory
  appears automatically at the next load process.
- Bug-cleaning (if there are still any;-)
- Maybe supporting of 1 or 2 more charsets
- Additional conversion parameters

A planned adaption to a @{"MUI" LINK "Credits"}-interface will not be developed.
The cause is that many users use TextConv with UAE, and MUI is very
slow under this conditions.

Eventually planned is a Windows-version of TextConv.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "History" "History"
@NEXT "Credits"
@PREV "Future"
@TOC "MAIN"
10. History

V1.51d/e: Second official AmiNet-release
          - CyberGuard- and EnforcerHit-free
          - Bug removed at the ASL-requester-management that
            sometimes caused a system crash.
          - english version

V1.50d:   Inofficial release, available on request
          - nearly complete new code
          - partial modular concept; conversion tables as external
            files
          - Use of a read-/write-buffer; this causes
            1) Size of the convertable files only limited by
               hard disk space
            2) About 5-20 times faster
          - Implementation of the Atari-format
          - Very ugly bug at the Macintosh-conversion removed
            (uncorrect char conversion at the ASCII-range 127-255)
          - New conversion modes:
            1) Remove control chars
            2) Convert only control chars
          - Changing the program classification from FREEWARE to
            @{"MAILWARE" LINK "Warranty"}

V1.2-1-4: Internal version numbers

V1.10d/e: Inofficial release, available on request
          - Warning about overwriting of files
          - Dynamic memory management, this causes that the max.
            size of the convertable files is only limited by
            the amount of free memory
          - Small change at the GUI, so that the whole window is
            visible at screens with a hight of 256 pixels.
          - Removing of some little bugs (correct on/off-switching of
            the gadgets)
          - english version

V1.00d:   First official AmiNet-release
          Awarded from the german Amiga-magazine "AmigaSpezial 2/96"
 


@ENDNODE

